**Statement of Work**

## Introduction

| Name of Project |
| :---- |
| *DIY Capture the Flag* |

| Contact  | Email/Cell |
| :---- | :---- |
| Sponsor:  | KdG Cybersecurity Program (Instructor TBD) |
| Stakeholder:  | KdG students and faculty using the CTF portal |
| Project Manager:  | matthias.adriaenssen@student.kdg.be |
| Team Member:  | sefkan.ozmen@student.kdg.be |
| Contractor/Vendor:  | Self-hosted stack using open-source components |

| Background |
| :---- |
| Modern cybersecurity courses benefit from hands-on practice. This project creates a deployable, self-contained Capture-the-Flag (CTF) environment consisting of a portal and multiple intentionally vulnerable microservices. It runs locally (Docker Desktop) and on Google Compute Engine (GCE) via a hardened startup script, enabling quick setup for workshops, labs and exams. |

| Purpose |
| :---- |
| Deliver a reproducible CTF platform with a curated set of beginner-friendly challenges, an accessible Dutch UI, and one-click provisioning on GCE. Instructors can spin up an instance for a class; students can browse to the VM IP and start solving without local installs. |

## Scope of Work

| To Be Done  | Resources Needed | Outcome | Time Involved | General Steps |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Dockerized CTF suite (portal + 3 services) | Docker, Flask, Python 3.11 | Local stack runs with health endpoints | 1 week | Scaffold services, add `/healthz`, environment-configurable flags, compose orchestration |
| GCE startup automation | Debian/Ubuntu VM, GCP access | One-command provisioning on a fresh VM | 2 days | Install Docker (official APT), clone repo with token, `docker compose up -d`, diagnostics when health fails |
| UX & accessibility polish | HTML/CSS, Jinja templates | Dutch portal, collapsible sections, click-to-reveal hints | 3 days | Improve contrast, dark mode, PRG flash messages, solved badges, ASCII banner |
| Documentation & runbook | Markdown, screenshots | README and step-by-step guide | 1–2 days | Usage, firewall rules (80, 443, 8001–8003), troubleshooting, teardown |

## Define Success

| *Detail what stakeholders/sponsor deem a successful completion of the project* |
| :---- |
| A student can visit the VM’s public IP (port 80), access the Dutch portal, launch each challenge, obtain flags, and submit them successfully; instructors can deploy from scratch on a new GCE VM using the provided script; documentation enables others to reproduce and troubleshoot the setup. |

## Requirements

| *Note any equipment, degrees or certification and travel time that will be required for the project here* |
| :---- |
| GCP project with permissions to create Debian/Ubuntu VMs; ability to add VPC firewall rules for TCP 80, 443, 8001–8003; Docker installed locally for development; optional Git personal access token for private clone; no travel required. |

## Other

| *Place here anything relevant to the project that was not captured above* |
| :---- |
| The challenges are intentionally vulnerable and must be run in a sandboxed environment. Do not expose to the public Internet without a firewall. Educational use only. |
